	raw-html: <p><strong>Programming Focus:</strong> This unit focuses on several types of analysis: analysis of problems to generate algorithms for their solution; analysis of the algorithms, especially of the time it takes to execute them, to optimize them; analysis of phenomena to generate models and simulations that give insight and help one generate and test hypotheses; and analysis of data, especially including visualization.</p>
    raw-html: <p>Students have been generating algorithms to solve problems from the start of this course, but have not yet focused on analyzing them for efficiency. For small enough computational problems, such analysis isn't needed. But modeling complex phenomena and handling large data sets requires understanding that there are sometimes alternative algorithms that reduce the impact of the size of a model on the time it takes to execute. In-depth coverage of this broad domain (computational complexity, data analysis, modeling and simulation) is beyond the scope of an introductory course, but this unit's projects in each of these areas will give students a good first-approximation understanding of these issues. </p>
	raw-html: <p>In discussing the running time of programs, we use the College Board terminology: "reasonable" for polynomial time and "unreasonable" for exponential time.  But you should understand that what's reasonable depends on the problem you're trying to solve.  If you're looking for a particular pattern in the billions of genes in the human genome, even a linear-time search is unreasonable.  DNA sequencing required contributions from biology, from electrical engineering, and so on.  But the most important contribution of computer science was the development of <em>sublinear</em> search algorithms.  For this reason and others, we <em>also</em> teach the more specific technical terms: linear time, quadratic time, and so on.</p>
	raw-html: <p>Many problems of practical importance can't realistically be solved because there is no known polynomial time algorithm.  (For some of these problems there are partial solutions that compute a "close enough" answer in polynomial time.)  But other problems can't be solved <em>in principle,</em> even if we had ultra-fast computers and all the time in the world.  Computer scientists think that non-computer methods (including human reasoning) can't solve those problems either; this is the "Church/Turing Thesis."  Because functions are first class data in Snap<em>!,</em> we can give a reasonably short proof of the uncomputability of the "halting function" in Lab 4.  But "short" doesn't mean "easy"; this is unquestionably the hardest lab in BJC.  The College Board wants your students to know that some functions are not computable, but they're happy if students take this on faith.  We think that at least some students will prefer not to take on faith something that can be proved using techniques they can understand.</p>
