	raw-html: <p><strong>Social Implications Focus:</strong> Computing in War</p>
		raw-html: <p>Students learn how computing innovations impact modern warfare and reflect upon the ethics of developing technology to kill people.  The question may make you uncomfortable, but we think it's unacceptable to split hairs about the more subtle effects of computing on society while ignoring the elephant in the room.  Your students may conclude that there are good reasons to develop military technology, but if so, they should be able to articulate their reasons.</p>

h3: Big Ideas 2, 3, 4, 5
        raw-html:<p>The big focus of Unit 5 is on analyzing <strong>algorithms (Big Idea 4)</strong> and <strong>data and information (Big Idea 3).</strong> Students explore various ways to process, create, analyze, and visualize data through their experiments and simulations relying and building on their experience with <strong>programming (Big Idea 5)</strong> and <strong>abstraction (Big Idea 2)</strong>.</p>
        
h3: Computational Thinking Practices P1, P2, P4, P5, P6
        raw-html:<p>Students <strong>create</strong> several <strong>computational artifacts (P2)</strong> including an extension of the <a href="/bjc-r/cur/programming/2-complexity/1-variables-games/1-number-guessing-game.html">number guessing game</a> from Unit 2 and a coin flipping simulator. Students <strong>analyze problems</strong> (e.g., list searching algorithms and data scaling) to create suitable algorithms for solving them, and they create a timer program to help them <strong>analyze programs (P4)</strong> for their computational efficiency. Students continue to <strong>connect computing (P1)</strong> to the human experience through their reading and discussions about copyrights and to <strong>communicate (P5)</strong> and <strong>collaborate (P6)</strong> through pair programming.</p>
	
